{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489709"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:27:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:27:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"724"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/724"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.71,0.05,0.08,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46930"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/724"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31704"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"3812"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9285"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12316"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46930"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 14-month history of lower abdominal discomfort and the passage of bright red blood at the time of defecation. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is a lifetime non-smoker and drinks two glasses of wine each night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 66/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Abdominal examination is normal. On rectal examination there is a circumferential tumour immediately above the anal canal. Following biopsy, the tumour is determined to be a colonic adenocarcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the next most appropriate investigation after colonoscopy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["LFTs","CT chest, abdomen and pelvis","CEA level","MRI pelvis","PET scan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lengthy history of change in bowel habits and PR bleeding increases the index of suspicion that the patient may already have metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst this patient will require a colonoscopy to look for other (synchronous) tumours in the colon and to define the proximal extension of the tumour visible at the anus, \u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest, abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is the next most appropriate investigation. In this setting, the first question to be answered is whether there is metastatic disease (i.e. what the stage of the malignancy is), be it to regional lymph nodes, or distant sites. Of the options, this investigation provides the greatest level of detail regarding the stage of disease. As such, the \u0027Optimal Care Pathway\u0027 for colorectal cancer recommends this as the next most appropriate investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECEA level\u003C/strong\u003E is a tumour marker that can be elevated in colorectal cancer. However, it lacks sensitivity and specificity for diagnosis. Its main role is in monitoring for recurrence after treatment, rather than initial staging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPET scans\u003C/strong\u003E have roles in assessing for metastatic disease, however these are not the most appropriate first-line investigations in this setting, as a CT scan will still show evidence of regional metastases to other more proximal sites (e.g. regional lymph nodes, liver). This investigation would be more appropriate in the setting of re-staging of disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E has a key role in the locoregional staging (T and N) of rectal cancer. This helps in the decision-making between treatment options (e.g. pre-operative radiotherapy, local excision, or surgical resection). In this case, MRI would only be done once a CT had excluded metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELFTs\u003C/strong\u003E may provide evidence of liver metastases if they are deranged. However, a CT scan is still required to confirm and further characterise any liver lesions. LFTs alone are not sufficient for staging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["CT chest, abdomen and pelvis is the next most appropriate initial investigation after colonoscopy in initial staging of colorectal cancer"],"references":["Cancer Council: Optimal care pathway for people with colorectal cancer [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.cancer.org.au/assets/pdf/colorectal-cancer-optimal-cancer-care-pathway","Bergin RJ, Whitfield K, White V, Milne RL, Emery JD, et al. Optimal care pathways: A national policy to improve quality of cancer care and address inequalities in cancer outcomes. J cancer policy. 2020 Sep 1;25:100245. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S2213538320300370?via%3Dihub","Dekker E, Tanis PJ, Vleugels JLA, et al. Colorectal cancer. Lancet 2019; 394:1467.80. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(19)32319-0/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31704"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"724"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31704"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-13T21:48:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-01T19:22:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"724"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46930"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https: